Unusual "black-backed" individual foraging on lawn with other robins and juncos adjacent to the parking lot. The back and scapular feathers were black-centered, which contrasted strongly with the rump. The white eye arcs were reduced in size, and the throat had an average mix of white and black feathering. The breast was a deep rufous with little scalloping compared to nearby robins. Black feathers on the head continued down the center of the nape and onto the back and scapulars, and even onto the sides of the breast. The sides of the nape were contrastingly gray-brown. The darkest individuals reported as nigrideus show a black head concolor with an entirely black nape that continues down the back. Bruce Mactavish discusses some birds similar to ours on his blog here- http://brucemactavish1.blogspot.com/2014/04/the-mythical-black-backed-newfoundland.html  This taxon is potentially dubious; nigrideus may represent a Newfoundland population or "just" extreme variation in all robins. Those who have written more extensively on the subject in recent history lean toward the "just variation" hypothesis and argue that black-backed individuals are found throughout the range of American Robin. However, most or all photos of black-backed individuals come from eastern Canada or the northeast US in winter (...but is there a bias in accepting nigrideus only from this region?).  https://www.sibleyguides.com/bird-info/american-robin/  Mengel (1965, see p. 360)- https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/om/om003.pdf

Observation Details: ***Rare, or so current records tell us, but the status of this subspecies is very uncertain due to the fact that most birders don’t even know it exists! First Westchester eBird record but one that is almost certainly an annual. While I was walking the last part of my loop around the pond, this Robin caught my eye as being notably dark. Now, we’ve all seen some dark Migratorious group robins, but this bird’s dark, burnished orange chest, mostly black throat, and very dark gray back with extensive black from the head bleeding into the nape indicated to me I had a Nigrideus on my hands! Thankfully this bird gave some awesome eye level views as it foraged in the leaf litter. Awesome subspecies and one I’m sure I’ve seen before and hope to see again! Photos to come

Observation Details: Unusual "black-backed" individual foraging on lawn with other robins and juncos adjacent to the parking lot. The back and scapular feathers were black-centered, which contrasted strongly with the rump. The white eye arcs were reduced in size, and the throat had an average mix of white and black feathering. The breast was a deep rufous with little scalloping compared to nearby robins. Black feathers on the head continued down the center of the nape and onto the back and scapulars, and even onto the sides of the breast. The sides of the nape were contrastingly gray-brown. The darkest individuals reported as nigrideus show a black head concolor with an entirely black nape that continues down the back. Bruce Mactavish discusses some birds similar to ours on his blog here- http://brucemactavish1.blogspot.com/2014/04/the-mythical-black-backed-newfoundland.html  This taxon is potentially dubious; nigrideus may represent a Newfoundland population or "just" extreme variation in all robins. Those who have written more extensively on the subject in recent history lean toward the "just variation" hypothesis and argue that black-backed individuals are found throughout the range of American Robin. However, most or all photos of black-backed individuals come from eastern Canada or the northeast US in winter (...but is there a bias in accepting nigrideus only from this region?).  https://www.sibleyguides.com/bird-info/american-robin/  Mengel (1965, see p. 360)- https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/om/om003.pdf

Media notes: This photo was the best quality of the several robin photos I took that afternoon. As may be seen from the photo, the bird was on the ground, which had grass and other short ground cover, and was in a very shady area because of multiple in-leaf trees in this park-like setting. Some sunlight, though, was coming through from my side of the bird, and it provided good illumination of the bird's top-side features. The dark spots in substantial numbers on the lower breast and belly of this individual seem to me to suggest that this is a youngster still not in full adult plumage on its underside. The others of this species seen that day all showed the darkish underside dots or spots, albeit in varying degrees.
Observation Details: Three of this species were noted early in our effort, and when on our walk we returned to the original area, only one of this species was seen. There might have been only three of this species in the area this day, for the late one might have been a remnant of the original group, an individual that had failed to move with the others. Alternatively, it might have been moving about the area independently of the original three. In conclusion, there were at least three American Robins seen on this occasion, and possibly there was a fourth that was foraging separately from the original three.

Observation Details: Adult male “Newfoundland Robin” with extreme amount of black on head/nape/center of back/tertials. Mostly black throat. Very extensive dark-rufous undersides. Large flock going crazy over berries. For whatever reason the Hawthorn trees dropped all their berries. Not sure if this was due to the temperature shift, but not a single berry remained on the trees. Many Robins gorging themselves on the berries, when the area got crowded, some would go eat Sumac or Rose hips instead. Watched for about an hour, then suddenly they all left.

Photos. As I was leaving area, I noticed flocks of CEWA and AMRO feeding on bush honeysuckle on the edge of the road so I pulled to the side, rolled down the window, and turned the engine off. Shockingly, the birds left the honeysuckle and attempted to drink water from a frozen puddle no more than 1.5' from the car. Remaining motionless and with no entering or departing vehicles, I was able to get some super photos.

Locality: Sevenmile Creek--Prickly Pear Land Trust (restricted access)
Observation Details: 3 singing, 1 from E of the property early in the survey. Within 5 minutes of the survey start I saw a robin perched briefly on the sewage lagoon fence at the start point, then fly W. At 0655 a male flew back to the sewage lagoon fence near the start point and then began singing, at the same time as the individual E of the property along the creek. The near AMRO then flew to a Russian-olive 20 m E of the fence and sang some more. I was a bit surprised to see one so far out in the field - I don't remember observing that last year. At 0707 I saw 2 AMRO on the sewage lagoon fence, neither vocal at that point. At 0710 I saw a robin in the field near the start point briefly, likely foraging, and then it flew off. Sometime around 0815 an AMRO (one of these two singers?) was singing from a willow in the E part of reach 4. At 0926, 3 AMRO flew upstream over the diversion, loosely together, at roughly 5x shrub height. Later I saw at least 3 robins near the recently constructed wetland in reach 2, including 1 singing for a time from a Chokecherry S of the wetland, and 2 foraging on the ground. 1 was a female for sure (very pale gray-brown head). I saw the other catch and swallow a large worm (photo of the last bit of the worm in its beak). That individual was foraging on the stream terrace ca 5-10 m S of the stream in an area where equipment has been traveling, with bare disturbed earth and short, lawn-like green grasses. I presume that the individual singing here was different from those singing downstream. At 0959 all 3 robins took off and flew upstream. Then ca 1 minute later another robin flew up from downstream and perched in a Chokecherry, calling. Later, saw 1 individual singing near "WIFL flats." On the return I saw a robin near the stream on the puddled mud in the NE portion of the constructed wetland. It had a worm at its feet; it jabbed at the worm several times with its beak, picking it up partway. I also heard a robin singing for a while in this area on the return.

Media notes: One of about 150+ Robins in a multi-day "feeding frenzy" around the perimeter of a large harvested winter cornfield.
Observation Details: Conservative estimate. Spent just over an hour doing as careful a count as possible, walking the field perimeter that has quite a few fruit-bearing trees and bushes along the fencelines (a walk of about 2 km - it's a large field!). Where there were fruit trees/bushes, there would be concentrations of Robins and Cedar Waxwings, but especially along the south edge of the field. I was being very conservative in my counting, but when you see 40 Robins fly across the field and there are still more than twice as many still along the other side of the field, it supports the conservative count of 150 that I had already calculated. It's entirely conceiveable that there might have even been 175-200, but I'll be conservative for the official record.

Observation Details: Found a young fledgling in the road, and quickly pulled over. After a narrow miss from a car, I attempted to relocate the bird, at which point it ran underneath my car. After about 15 mins, the person with me rolled the car forward, and I was able to pick up the bird and move it about 100 feet away from the road, despite the bird’s unwillingness to cooperate. As I moved the young bird, an adult, which I hope and presume was the mother, flew near where I put the fledgling. The fledgling chirped a few times, and the adult responded. The bird did seem a little stressed, likely from both the road traffic and me holding it, but hopefully it’s able to survive.

Observation Details: One juvenile

5 heard singing only.  Just north of Oak Bridge, a nest with three young. I saw one was very actively bobbing up and down with its mouth full, and when I got the bind on it, it was trying to swallow a small mouse. I have never seen such a thing before.  It was not going well,  I took some pictures and short video, but I did not have it to stay and watch the process. But I ran into a couple of people as I went up the trail, and pointed the nest out to them. By then a parent had returned and all three were begging food in the normal fashion.   I thought there was No sign of the mouse, but reviewing my photos, I can see the tail sticking out of the nestling's mouth. So I guess it actually swallowed the mouse.   How did the mouse come to be there, surely a Robin wouldn't think it was a suitable food item?  As a follow up, I passed the nest a few days later and there were still three nestlings, one now much larger than the other two. So I guess the baby had no ill-effects from the meal.  A selection of photos is attached. I also have a video, but eBird doesn't let me upload videos.

Observation Details: Leucitic robin sighted and photographed near lighthouse

Strikingly patterned individual, far to the dark end of the spectrum for variation in this species. The jury still seems to be out regarding the full story with this subspecies and how reliably it can be identified in the field, but this bird appears to be as strong a candidate as any and is a good sight darker than many putative nigrideus that I've seen bandied about online. Extensive black plumage spilling down the neck and upperparts, forming a gradual gradient from all-black to dark with faint pale edging rather than a sharp cutoff between black and gray at the base of the skull. Even the rump and lower back seemed to be a darker shade of gray than typical migratorius birds. Noticeably reduced white markings on the throat and around the eyes, adding to the overall very dark-headed impression and contrasting dramatically with the bold, banana yellow bill. Underparts seemed especially rich in coloration, a deep reddish-orange without much pale edging except towards the lower flanks. Wet feathers from the dewy grass made the belly a bit difficult to assess, but the undertail coverts also appeared to show particularly strong, dark markings

Observation Details: very fun experience today - I rarely see robins foraging on lawns anymore ever since returning after the summer, not very sure why, but today south of the sharon dr. intersection (the road going to pennswood community garden) north of the parking spot of 3 cars, there were 3 robins foraging on the lawn!! like always robins are really confiding and allow me to watch them forage no problem. I squatted down low to take some pictures before recording videos of how they catch their worms - apparently they tilt their head down quite low over the grass (about 3-4cm above) and it seems like they're listening to the worms - I've read somewhere before that they do that, not sure if that is true. but then after doing that for about 5 seconds they yank a worm out of the ground with surprising accuracy which is very impressive! very fun watching robins catch worms after an entire summer of not seeing them doing so.

Counted at least 32 on the ground, in the Pecan Grove area, and then estimated at least 40 to 50, when additional birds were seen flushing up into trees further up ahead (when apparently one of the RSHA flew down the nearby creek).  Several of the American Robins (at least a half dozen of the birds seen up close) were hatch-year birds, still retaining remnants of juvenal plumage (see photo).  A large number of AMROs have been seen in this area during the breeding season during at least the last two years. I suspect many of these are birds that breed in the nearby Meadowlakes community (which is dominated by large shade trees and appears very typical of nesting habitat for AMROs).

Observation Details: ***Rare, or so current records tell us, but the status of this subspecies is very uncertain due to the fact that most birders don’t even know it exists! First Westchester eBird record but one that is almost certainly an annual. While I was walking the last part of my loop around the pond, this Robin caught my eye as being notably dark. Now, we’ve all seen some dark Migratorious group robins, but this bird’s dark, burnished orange chest, mostly black throat, and very dark gray back with extensive black from the head bleeding into the nape indicated to me I had a Nigrideus on my hands! Thankfully this bird gave some awesome eye level views as it foraged in the leaf litter. Awesome subspecies and one I’m sure I’ve seen before and hope to see again! Photos to come

Observation Details: First time since their arrival on January 5th they've used the house and surrounding trees as a centralized location for the day as a large flock. Constant activity all day long, nonstop movement and vocalizing. First time they've actually came into the yard and used the bird baths. Count is a minimum. No way to get a great count, Only moment when there was a quick fly away there was easily 50+ in the group just to return right away in different areas. Possible there was up to 150 moving about.
